  "prompt": "Why is oxalic acid soluble in water?",
  "response": "Oxalic acid is soluble in water due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds with water molecules. Here are the key reasons behind its solubility:\n\n1. **Polarity**: Oxalic acid (C\u2082H\u2082O\u2084) is a polar molecule. The presence of two carboxyl groups (-COOH) in its structure makes it capable of forming dipole-dipole interactions with water, which is also a polar solvent.\n\n2. **Hydrogen Bonding**: The carboxyl groups in oxalic acid can form hydrogen bonds with water molecules. Each -COOH group has an oxygen atom with a lone pair of electrons that can act as a hydrogen bond acceptor, and a hydrogen atom that can act as a hydrogen bond donor. This allows oxalic acid to integrate well into the water's hydrogen-bonding network.\n\n3. **Ionization**: Oxalic acid is a weak diprotic acid, meaning it can donate two protons (H\u207a ions) to water, forming oxalate ions (C\u2082O\u2084\u00b2\u207b). These ions can interact with water molecules through ion-dipole forces, further enhancing solubility.\n\n\\[\n\\text{C}_2\\text{H}_2\\text{O}_4 \\rightarrow \\text{H}^+ + \\text{HC}_2\\text{O}_4^-\n\\]\n\\[\n\\text{HC}_2\\text{O}_4^- \\rightarrow \\text{H}^+ + \\text{C}_2\\text{O}_4^{2-}\n\\]\n\n4. **Small Molecular Size**: The relatively small size of the oxalic acid molecule allows it to fit easily between water molecules, facilitating its dissolution.\n\nThese factors combined make oxalic acid highly soluble in water, with a solubility of approximately 90-100 grams per liter at room temperature.",
